response:
I have a complete picture. Here's the full diagnosis:

---

## Diagnosis

**The bug exists at two independent levels in the flex layout.**

### Level 1 — The outer container can wrap
`.navInner` is `display: flex; justify-content: space-between` but has **no `flex-wrap: nowrap`**. At narrow viewports, the browser's default `flex-wrap: wrap` is inherited, which means `.logo` and `.links` are treated as flex items that *may* wrap onto a second row. When the combined intrinsic widths exceed the container, the `.logo` block itself drops to row 2 — this is the wrap the user sees.

### Level 2 — `.logo` has `flex-shrink: 0` but `.links` has no explicit `flex-shrink`
`.links` has `min-width: 0` (good — allows it to shrink), but because `.logo` already has `flex-shrink: 0` and the container *can* wrap, once the `.links` column can't compress further, the next escape valve the browser finds is wrapping the row — taking the whole `.logo` to a second line.

### What's already correct
- `.logo` → `flex-shrink: 0` ✅
- `.logoMark` → `flex-shrink: 0` ✅  
- `.logoText` → `white-space: nowrap` ✅  
- `.links` → `min-width: 0` ✅  

The internal text wrapping is protected. **Only the outer row wrap is unprotected.**

### Root Cause
**AP-066 — Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text.** The `.navInner` flex row lacks `flex-wrap: nowrap`, allowing the browser to wrap the logo block onto a second row as a flex-wrap escape valve. `flex-shrink: 0` on a child only protects against *compression* — it does not prevent the flex *row* from wrapping when the container is narrower than the children.

---

## Fix

### File 1: `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

Three targeted changes:

1. **Add `flex-wrap: nowrap` to `.navInner`** — seals the outer row against wrapping.
2. **Add `min-width: 0` + `flex: 1 1 0` to `.links`** — makes the links side the designated yield zone: it absorbs all compression and never pushes the logo off-row.
3. **Tighten the `.tagline` comment** to explicitly state it is the *only* element permitted to wrap internally.

```scss
.navInner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  // IDENTITY PRIORITY: never let the nav row wrap. The logo is a hard-frozen
  // flex item (flex-shrink: 0 on .logo). The .links side is the sole yield
  // zone — it compresses first, and the tagline inside it may wrap to 2 lines.
  // If the viewport is so narrow that even that isn't enough, the layout clips
  // horizontally rather than wrapping the logo to a second row.
  flex-wrap: nowrap;
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}

.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
  // IDENTITY PRIORITY TIER 1: The logo is the site's core identity line.
  // flex-shrink: 0  — never compress this element under flex pressure.
  // flex-wrap: nowrap on .navInner — never allow this block to be pushed
  // to a second row. These two rules together are non-negotiable. See AP-066.
  flex-shrink: 0;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}

.links {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--portfolio-spacer-3x);
  // IDENTITY PRIORITY TIER 2: .links is the designated yield zone.
  // flex: 1 1 0 — grow to fill available space, shrink freely, start from 0.
  // min-width: 0 — allows shrinking below intrinsic content width.
  // The tagline child may wrap to 2 lines. Nav links are allowed to disappear
  // at very narrow widths. Nothing here is allowed to push the logo off its row.
  flex: 1 1 0;
  min-width: 0;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}
```

### File 2: `docs/design-anti-patterns.md`

**Amend AP-066** to elevate it from a flex-compression rule to the full Identity Priority Tier doctrine — capturing both the compression axis (already covered) and the row-wrap axis (the actual failure mode here). The user's principle is clear: *logo and nav identity lines never wrap under any pressure, ever*.

Find the existing `<a id="ap-066"></a>` block and replace it entirely:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE** — amended FB-146 (nav logo row-wrap axis added)

**Trigger:** A nav logo or core identity line wraps to two lines, collapses,
or is pushed to a second flex row under viewport squeeze.

**Why it's wrong:** The logo is not a flexible UI element — it is the site's
primary identity signal. Any layout that allows it to wrap, compress, or
relocate under pressure communicates that the brand is negotiable. It is not.
This is a non-negotiable UX hard-stop: the logo never loses integrity at any
viewport width. If something must yield, it is always the secondary content
beside the logo — never the logo itself.

**Two distinct failure axes — both must be guarded:**

| Axis | Failure | Guard |
|------|---------|-------|
| Compression | Logo text wraps internally (e.g., "Yilan" / "Gao") | `flex-shrink: 0` on `.logo`, `white-space: nowrap` on `.logoText` |
| Row wrap | Entire logo block pushes to a second flex row | `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the flex container (`.navInner`) |

**`flex-shrink: 0` alone is insufficient.** It prevents the logo from
*compressing*, but does not prevent the flex *row* from wrapping when the
container is narrower than the sum of its children. Both axes must be locked.

**Identity Priority Tiers — rule for every nav/header layout:**

```
TIER 1 — FROZEN:   Logo / site name. Never wraps. Never shrinks. Never moves.
                   CSS: flex-shrink: 0 + white-space: nowrap on text +
                        flex-wrap: nowrap on container.

TIER 2 — YIELDS:   Secondary nav content (tagline, links, identity blurb).
                   Compresses first. May wrap internally to 2 lines.
                   CSS: flex: 1 1 0; min-width: 0 on the links container.

TIER 3 — OPTIONAL: Auxiliary chrome (CTAs, theme toggle, utility links).
                   May hide at narrow widths.
```

**Correct implementation:**
```scss
// Container — lock the row
.navInner {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: nowrap;       // ← row never wraps
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
}

// Tier 1 — logo block, frozen
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;          // ← never compresses
}
.logoText {
  white-space: nowrap;     // ← text never line-breaks internally
}

// Tier 2 — links side, designated yield zone
.links {
  flex: 1 1 0;             // ← grows to fill, shrinks freely
  min-width: 0;            // ← allows shrinking below intrinsic width
}
```

**The tagline / identity blurb** ("Designer, AI systems experience…") lives
inside `.links` and is explicitly permitted to wrap to 2 lines — that is the
intended pressure release valve. Its max-lines cap (`-webkit-line-clamp: 2`)
prevents it from spilling into site content below the nav.

**See:** FB-146. Previously this anti-pattern only documented the compression
axis; FB-146 revealed the row-wrap axis is the more common failure.
```

### File 3: `docs/design-feedback-log.md`

Add **FB-227** at the top of the log (newest-first order), and update the `Last updated` header:

```markdown
**Last updated:** 2026-04-27 (FB-227: Nav logo row-wrap axis — `flex-wrap: nowrap` missing from `.navInner`. AP-066 amended to codify Identity Priority Tiers doctrine. Prior: ...)

---

<a id="fb-227"></a>
## FB-227: Nav logo "Yilan Gao" wrapping to two lines — row-wrap axis unguarded

**Date:** 2026-04-27
**Status:** RESOLVED

**Feedback:** The nav logo "Yilan Gao" wraps to two lines at narrow viewport
widths. Logo and navigation identity lines must never wrap or compromise —
this is a non-negotiable principle. The personal identity blurb
("Designer, AI systems experience…") may wrap to two lines; that is the
correct pressure release valve.

**Root cause:** `.navInner` lacked `flex-wrap: nowrap`. `flex-shrink: 0` on
`.logo` guards against compression but not row-wrap. When the browser ran out
of horizontal space, it wrapped the entire `.logo` block to a second row.
`.links` also lacked `flex: 1 1 0`, so there was no clear designated yield zone.

**Fix:**
- `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`:
  - Added `flex-wrap: nowrap` to `.navInner`
  - Added `flex: 1 1 0` and explicit `justify-content: flex-end` to `.links`
  - Comments updated to reflect Identity Priority Tiers

**Codified:** AP-066 amended — Identity Priority Tiers (Tier 1 Frozen / Tier 2
Yields / Tier 3 Optional) added. Row-wrap axis documented as the second
distinct failure mode alongside the original compression axis.

**See:** AP-066, FB-146 (original occurrence).
```

---

## Principle

This fix is grounded in **AP-066 — Identity Priority Tiers**, now formally elevated:

> **The logo is not a flexible layout element.** `flex-shrink: 0` guards the *compression* axis (text wraps internally). `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the container guards the *row-wrap* axis (block pushed to a second line). Both are required. Anything that yields under viewport pressure belongs in Tier 2 (`.links`, the tagline) — never in Tier 1 (the logo). The tagline's 2-line wrap is the *intentional* relief valve; it proves the system is working correctly. The logo being on one line at all times proves the identity is intact.

The three changes (one line of SCSS, one conceptual upgrade in AP-066, one feedback log entry) lock this permanently. Any future agent touching the nav will hit AP-066 immediately and find the full tier doctrine — not just a partial rule about `flex-shrink`.

